You do not know what I am going through. If I had money, I could get a method to end my misery. I wish for my last days on earth not to be full of this illness We need this. You want us to die from this illness, but we want it to be over.”76 These words are an apt summary of the arguments being pursued by those opposing separate reporting requirements for abortions in South Sudan.
It is essential that all reporting requirements on abortion in South Sudan are scrupulously implemented, because meaningful reporting flows the way of the country’s upper echelons. The GPW requires that publicly available data include “the number and of women and children under age five who arrive at health services with a suspicion or confirmation of an obstetric complication” and “the number of women and girls whose complications were successfully managed at health facilities and those who died because their complications could not be managed”.77 If these reporting requirements were to change, the Genuine Progress in Women’s Health would be jeopardised. Health ministries should also ensure that the Health Management Information System (HMIS) at the state and county level provides vital information on the barriers and health outcomes for women’s access to adequate reproductive and sexual health services.
